Use a single data structure to represent the queue, such as an array or a linked list.

Each message in the queue should have a unique ID and a payload. Optionally, it can also have a TTL field that specifies how long the message should be retained in the queue.

Use a publish-subscribe (pub-sub) model to allow multiple publishers and consumers to access the queue. Publishers should be able to add new messages to the end of the queue, while consumers should be able to read messages from the front of the queue.

To implement the pull-based model, consumers should be responsible for requesting messages from the queue instead of receiving them automatically. This can be done by exposing a pull function that consumers can call to retrieve messages. The function should take an optional parameter for the maximum number of messages to retrieve at once.

Implement a mechanism for managing message TTL. One way to do this is to periodically check the queue for expired messages and remove them. This can be done using a background task or a timer. Alternatively, the pull function can also check for expired messages and remove them before returning them to the consumer.

To ensure thread-safety and prevent data races, use synchronization primitives such as locks or semaphores to guard access to the shared data structure.
